cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.CC

The paper deals with coding and information theory problems related to multiple descriptions and diversity coding. The use of network coding ideas and the focus on achieving a certain rate region suggest that the paper belongs to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The mention of Gaussian multiple descriptions and the use of inner and outer bounds suggest that the paper may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. The use of decoders and subsets of encoded messages suggests that the paper may belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The mention of source-separation coding and the use of geometric structures suggest that the paper may also belong to the Signal and Image Processing (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the use of templates and the focus on rate regions suggest that the paper may belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
